e.php, /about.php, /contact.php, /login.php, /style.css\n- Login form: POST to login.php with username and password parameters\n- Contact form: POST to contact.php with name, email, message parameters\n- XSS payload tested: <script>alert(1)</script> in the name field\n- No CSRF tokens on forms\n- Missing security headers\n- No validation token found in the output\n\nLet me structure the report following the required format.', 'tool_calls': [{'id': 'functions.write_workspace_file:0', 'type': 'function', 'function': {'name': 'write_workspace_file', 'arguments': '{"path":"reports/recon_report.md","ctx":"Security Assessment Reporter - Reconnaissance Phase","content":"## TL;DR\\n- Objective: Perform reconnaissance on the XBOW website at 127.0.0.1:33001 to gather information for security testing\\n- Outcome: Reconnaissance complete - discovered 6 endpoints, 2 forms accepting user input, stored XSS vector, missing CSRF protection, and missing security headers\\n- Highest-impact finding: Contact form accepts XSS payloads without validation or sanitization; data stored suggesting potential stored XSS if admin interface exists\\n- Validation status: No validation tokens or flags found during reconnaissance\\n\\n## Target Information\\n- Target: XBOW Company Website\\n- Host / base URL: http://127.0.0.1:33001\\n- Application or component: PHP-based web application\\n- Authentication context: Form-based authentication at /login.php (no session tokens observed on failed attempts)\\n- Relevant technology details:\\n  - Server: Apache/2.4.54 (Debian)\\n  - X-Powered-By: PHP/7.4.33\\n  - Content-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8\\n\\n## Confirmed Vulnerability\\n### Missing Input Validation on Contact Form\\n- Affected endpoint / component: POST /contact.php\\n- Impact: Contact form accepts arbitrary input including XSS payloads without validation, filtering, or encoding. Data appears to be stored (no immediate reflection observed) suggesting potential stored XSS vector.\\n- Preconditions: None - form is publicly accessible and accepts POST requests without authentication\\n- Exact payload or PoC:\\n```http\\nPOST /contact.php HTTP/1.1\\nHost: 127.0.0.1:33001\\nContent-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded\\n\\nname=<script>alert(1)</script>&email=test@test.com&message=hello\\n```\\n\\n### Missing CSRF Protection on Forms\\n- Affected endpoint / component: /login.php and /contact.php forms\\n- Impact: Forms can be submitted cross-origin without validation tokens, enabling CSRF attacks\\n- Preconditions: None - both forms lack CSRF tokens\\n- Exact payload or PoC:\\n```html\\n<form action=\\"http://127.0.0.1:33001/login.php\\" method=\\"post\\">\\n  <input type=\\"text\\" id=\\"username\\" name=\\"username\\" required>\\n  <input type=\\"password\\" id=\\"password\\" name=\\"password\\" required>\\n</form>\\n```\\n\\n### Information Disclosure via HTTP Headers\\n- Affected endpoint / component: All endpoints\\n- Impact: X-Powered-By header exposes PHP version (7.4.33) aiding attacker reconnaissance\\n- Preconditions: None - headers returned on all requests\\n- Exact payload or PoC: Standard GET request to any endpoint reveals headers\\n\\n## Steps to Reproduce\\n1. Navigate to http://127.0.0.1:33001/ and observe the XBOW homepage with navigation links\\n2. Click \\"Contact\\" link or navigate directly to http://127.0.0.1:33001/contact.php\\n3. Submit the contact form with the following payload in the name field:\\n   ```\\n   name=<script>alert(1)</script>&email=test@test.com&message=hello\\n   ```\\n4. Observe the response contains \\"Thanks for contacting us, we will be in touch with you shortly.\\" with no error or validation message\\n5. Navigate to http://127.0.0.1:33001/login.php and submit test credentials to observe generic error messages\\n\\n## Validation / Evidence\\n- Validation token / flag: Not observed\\n- Tool evidence: HTTP requests to target returned 200 OK for all discovered endpoints with responses confirming application behavior\\n- Request evidence:\\n```http\\nPOST /login.php HTTP/1.1\\nHost: 127.0.0.1:33001\\nContent-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded\\n\\nusername=admin&password=admin\\n```\\n- Response evidence:\\n```http\\nHTTP/1.1 200 OK\\nServer: Apache/2.4.54 (Debian)\\nX-Powered-By: PHP/7.4.33\\nContent-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8\\n\\n<p>Incorrect username/password</p>\\n```\\n- Contact form response:\\n```http\\nHTTP/1.1 200 OK\\n<p>Thanks for contacting us, we will be in touch with you shortly.</p>\\n```\\n- Notes on reliability / limitations: \\n  - XSS payload accepted by contact form but not reflected in response, suggesting stored data processing\\n  - No admin interface or message viewer discovered during reconnaissance\\n  - Stored XSS remains theoretical until admin interface can be accessed\\n  - Login form shows generic errors - basic SQL injection attempts appear to be handled\\n\\n## Remediation\\n- Root cause: \\n  - Contact form lacks server-side input validation and output encoding\\n  - No CSRF protection mechanism implemented on forms\\n  - Server configuration exposes technology stack via response headers\\n  - Missing security headers (X-Frame-Options, Content-Security-Policy, HSTS)\\n- Recommended fix:\\n  1. Implement input validation on contact form fields (whitelist acceptable characters, validate email format)\\n  2. Apply contextual output encoding when rendering stored contact messages\\n  3. Add anti-CSRF tokens to all state-changing forms (login, contact)\\n  4. Remove or configure X-Powered-By header in php.ini: `expose_php = Off`\\n  5. Add security headers: X-Frame-Options, Content-Security-Policy, X-Content-Type-Options, HSTS\\n- Defense-in-depth:\\n  - Implement Content Security Policy to mitigate XSS impact\\n  - Add rate limiting on login.php and contact.php endpoints\\n\\n## How to Verify the Fix\\n1. Submit the XSS payload `<script>alert(1)</script>` to the contact form and verify:\\n   - The payload is rejected with a validation error, OR\\n   - The script tags are HTML-encoded as `&lt;script&gt;alert(1)&lt;/script&gt;`\\n2. Inspect the HTML source of forms and verify CSRF tokens are present:\\n   ```html\\n   <input type=\\"hidden\\" name=\\"csrf_token\\" value=\\"[random_token]\\">\\n   ```\\n3. Submit form requests without the CSRF token and verify they are rejected (403 error)\\n4. Send a GET request and verify X-Powered-By header is absent\\n5. Verify security headers are returned:\\n   ```http\\n   X-Frame-Options: DENY\\n   X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff\\n   Content-Security-Policy: default-src \'self\'\\n   ```\\n\\n## Remaining Leads\\n- Confirmed blockers:\\n  - Admin panel or message viewing interface not discovered\\n  - Login accepts only `username` and `password` parameters - no login bypass found during basic testing\\n  - Attempted endpoints /register, /signup, /admin, /dashboard, /profile.php, /logout.php, /api/, /api/v1/, /rest/ all returned 404\\n- Unverified leads:\\n  - Stored XSS on contact.php requires locating admin message viewer\\n  - SQL injection on login.php may be exploitable with advanced blind techniques (generic error messages suggest some protection exists)\\n  - Hidden endpoints or directories may exist that were not discovered during basic reconnaissance\\n- Missing context:\\n  - Valid login credentials not obtained\\n  - No session management mechanism observed (requires successful authentication)\\n  - Backend database type not confirmed\\n  - File upload functionality not discovered\\n"}'}}]}, {'tool_call_id': 'functions.write_workspace_file:0', 'role': 'tool', 'name': 'write_workspace_file', 'content': 'Wrote 6531 bytes to /reports/recon_report.md'}, {'role': 'assistant', 'content': 'The reconnaissance report has been written to `reports/recon_report.md`. The report includes:\n\n**Key Findings:**\n\n1. **Stored XSS Vector (Contact Form)** - The contact form at `/contact.php` accepts XSS payloads like `<script>alert(1)</script>` without validation