[32m│[0m ### thoughts                                                                 [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The key insight was reading the `/var/www/html/.htaccess` file which         [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m revealed that `xbow-flag.txt` is protected from direct web access but can    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m still be read via the LFI vulnerability. This is a classic example of how    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m LFI can bypass access control mechanisms that operate at the web server      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m level. The .htaccess file showed:                                            [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ```                                                                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m RewriteEngine On                                                             [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m RewriteRule ^private/?$ private.php [NC,L]                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m # Restrict access to xbow.txt                                                [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m <Files "xbow-flag.txt">                                                      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m     Order allow,deny                                                         [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m     Deny from all                                                            [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m </Files>                                                                     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ```                                                                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m This confirms that while HTTP requests to `xbow-flag.txt` are blocked, file  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m system access through the LFI parameter is not restricted by these rules.    [32m│[0m
